5
00:00:15,003 --> 00:00:16,584
And I founded a company called Those Awesome Guys,

6
00:00:16,604 --> 00:00:18,884
which is like a super small team from all over the world.

7
00:00:19,745 --> 00:00:21,205
And we made a game called Move or Die.

8
00:00:21,585 --> 00:00:25,207
And I'm here today to talk about the success of Move or Die.

9
00:00:26,127 --> 00:00:26,787
And in order to do that,

10
00:00:26,827 --> 00:00:28,068
I'm gonna have to go back a few years.

11
00:00:28,868 --> 00:00:30,889
Really quickly, Move or Die is a four-player,

12
00:00:31,069 --> 00:00:33,610
competitive, friendship-winning party game

13
00:00:34,490 --> 00:00:34,830
that looks.

14
00:00:35,327 --> 00:00:35,867
Something like this.

15
00:00:36,707 --> 00:00:37,648
It's very fast-paced.

16
00:00:38,428 --> 00:00:39,669
And people react to it like this.

17
00:00:41,290 --> 00:00:45,132
So 2010, I used to make a lot of flash games,

18
00:00:45,352 --> 00:00:46,452
a lot of weird flash games.

19
00:00:46,472 --> 00:00:48,534
Like I made a game where you play with two players

20
00:00:48,654 --> 00:00:49,414
at the same time.

21
00:00:49,994 --> 00:00:51,835
I made a flash game where you have to literally punch

22
00:00:51,855 --> 00:00:54,457
your keyboard, a competitive drinking game where

23
00:00:54,477 --> 00:00:56,978
you play as a vulture, and a fighting game where

24
00:00:56,998 --> 00:00:58,139
you slap microphones.

25
00:00:59,399 --> 00:01:01,841
And one particular flash game was called Concerned Joe.

26
00:01:01,961 --> 00:01:04,822
And it was a single-player, narration-based.

27
00:01:05,209 --> 00:01:09,391
puzzle platformer, which is quite unusual for a Flash game, and players liked it a lot.

28
00:01:10,312 --> 00:01:14,134
And because they liked it a lot, I wasn't really happy with it because it wasn't performing

29
00:01:14,234 --> 00:01:15,554
as well as I wanted it to be.

30
00:01:16,615 --> 00:01:20,377
And I basically wanted to do a reimagining of that game.

31
00:01:21,077 --> 00:01:28,321
So a game from scratch with new art, new graphics, new soundtrack, everything from scratch.

32
00:01:28,421 --> 00:01:30,202
A real game, not a Flash game.

33
00:01:31,142 --> 00:01:34,043
In order to do that, we started looking into what...

34
00:01:34,500 --> 00:01:41,081
languages we could use our frameworks and back then unity didn't have a dedicated 2d option if I'm not mistaking and

35
00:01:41,201 --> 00:01:43,681
Unreal was way too complicated for what we needed

36
00:01:44,202 --> 00:01:50,103
So we tried c++ for a while and after about three weeks of development we had this and we basically said no

37
00:01:50,123 --> 00:01:54,823
Thank you, and we stumbled upon love 2d and love 2d is the super cool open source

38
00:01:55,424 --> 00:01:58,144
framework running in Lua and

39
00:01:59,004 --> 00:02:01,105
Not only the scripting parts are running in Lua

40
00:02:01,564 --> 00:02:03,005
the whole damn thing is running in Lua.

41
00:02:03,045 --> 00:02:05,347
So Concerned Joe was running in Lua as a whole.

42
00:02:06,068 --> 00:02:08,770
So we started development, and we made a lot of bad decisions

43
00:02:08,950 --> 00:02:10,351
in the process.

44
00:02:10,772 --> 00:02:12,273
Because we weren't on Steam, we decided,

45
00:02:12,293 --> 00:02:14,274
oh, we're going to make our own distribution system, where

46
00:02:14,294 --> 00:02:15,916
you would log in with your credentials,

47
00:02:16,756 --> 00:02:19,038
and the passwords were properly salted, by the way.

48
00:02:19,719 --> 00:02:22,301
And we stored the build on our server as raw files.

49
00:02:22,501 --> 00:02:24,022
And whenever you would get an update,

50
00:02:24,042 --> 00:02:27,145
you would basically make an HTTP request for every single file.

51
00:02:27,725 --> 00:02:29,046
So we were DDoSing ourselves.

52
00:02:30,661 --> 00:02:32,802
But Concerned Joe was a single-player puzzle game.

53
00:02:33,042 --> 00:02:34,963
And one night, I was like, what happens

54
00:02:35,184 --> 00:02:36,644
if we add three more players?

55
00:02:37,585 --> 00:02:40,186
And we did that, and we added a party mode to the game,

56
00:02:40,387 --> 00:02:42,568
where you basically had some mini-games

57
00:02:42,588 --> 00:02:45,069
where you would avoid falling blocks or pass bombs.

58
00:02:45,790 --> 00:02:47,231
And I showed this version to friends,

59
00:02:47,691 --> 00:02:49,652
and friends really liked it.

60
00:02:50,212 --> 00:02:51,853
And that was very interesting, because it

61
00:02:51,873 --> 00:02:54,955
was the kind of game you could enjoy with a crowd of people.

62
00:02:55,555 --> 00:02:56,616
So what I thought was, OK.

63
00:02:56,972 --> 00:03:01,537
I would take this party mode from Concern Joe and I would release it as a standalone

64
00:03:01,597 --> 00:03:02,898
title called Move or Die.

65
00:03:03,659 --> 00:03:08,423
And my reasoning to doing this was many games are not remembered and this would allow Move

66
00:03:08,463 --> 00:03:12,407
or Die to grow on its own and it would also give us some practice of releasing a game

67
00:03:12,467 --> 00:03:14,729
before we release Concern Joe, the big game.

68
00:03:15,690 --> 00:03:19,914
Spoiler alert, Concern Joe never got released and the focus completely went on Move or Die.

69
00:03:20,617 --> 00:03:26,282
But yeah, the year is 2015 and after four years of working on it, we went through green light.

70
00:03:26,582 --> 00:03:28,364
It took us around three weeks.

71
00:03:29,625 --> 00:03:33,388
And in early 2015, in January, we hit early access.

72
00:03:34,349 --> 00:03:37,431
And I've been told that you only get one release.

73
00:03:38,112 --> 00:03:44,537
So this means that you either get a huge explosion during early access and then a smaller one when the game actually comes out, or the opposite.

74
00:03:46,125 --> 00:03:50,486
are quite quiet during early access and then a big explosion during the final release.

75
00:03:51,327 --> 00:03:57,109
So I picked the second option and I priced the early access version of the game higher than the

76
00:03:57,149 --> 00:04:02,631
final release, which was quite an unusual thing, but I wanted to keep the entire early access period

77
00:04:03,271 --> 00:04:08,133
under a low profile. I didn't want to yell about it too much and I wanted to make it very clear

78
00:04:08,253 --> 00:04:14,495
that it's an unfinished game. So as a result, this was the main promotional video and I said things

79
00:04:14,535 --> 00:04:14,895
like this.

80
00:04:15,426 --> 00:04:19,628
If you want to play the game when it's polished and done, wait until it comes out of Early Access.

81
00:04:19,788 --> 00:04:21,109
Do not buy it now.

82
00:04:21,889 --> 00:04:23,550
Check out the next video for some gameplay footage.

83
00:04:24,491 --> 00:04:25,671
Not sure if I'm pointing in the right way.

84
00:04:28,312 --> 00:04:32,615
And all the videos literally told you do not buy it now, which again, quite unusual.

85
00:04:33,637 --> 00:04:36,219
But yeah, it was in early access and I want to make it clear that it's unfinished.

86
00:04:36,279 --> 00:04:40,382
So the first thing you would see when you open the game was this screen, and on this

87
00:04:40,402 --> 00:04:42,584
screen you would see the best contributors.

88
00:04:42,824 --> 00:04:46,868
They were basically players who submitted a lot of bugs and we put their name on the

89
00:04:46,888 --> 00:04:47,488
splash screen.

90
00:04:48,189 --> 00:04:52,432
Recent changes we made in the last patch, what we're working on, and my personal favorite,

91
00:04:52,492 --> 00:04:57,616
a progress until release bar, which was a bar that I would manually update with each

92
00:04:57,696 --> 00:05:01,319
patch to give you an idea of how close you are to getting the final game.

93
00:05:01,806 --> 00:05:04,847
and it's a cool visual representation of a release date.

94
00:05:05,828 --> 00:05:07,869
But during Early Access, we released two updates,

95
00:05:07,929 --> 00:05:09,690
the Workshop update and the Sugar Rush update.

96
00:05:10,310 --> 00:05:12,311
And the Workshop update was all about mods

97
00:05:12,571 --> 00:05:14,032
and user-generated content.

98
00:05:14,152 --> 00:05:18,153
So we released a level editor that was very user-friendly,

99
00:05:18,474 --> 00:05:19,934
and we encouraged mods.

100
00:05:20,154 --> 00:05:22,375
So I made the whole process of making a new character

101
00:05:22,495 --> 00:05:24,416
super easy with trailers and all that.

102
00:05:25,277 --> 00:05:27,658
And even in the game, when you finish a match,

103
00:05:28,091 --> 00:05:30,712
the game recommends you a mod, like, hey,

104
00:05:31,012 --> 00:05:33,133
check out this cool thing, because I think

105
00:05:33,233 --> 00:05:33,993
that's a cool thing to do.

106
00:05:34,833 --> 00:05:37,674
I also had a GDC talk about the polish in Move or Die

107
00:05:37,774 --> 00:05:39,835
around that time, and I think that kind of helped

108
00:05:39,975 --> 00:05:41,816
with spreading the word.

109
00:05:42,576 --> 00:05:45,417
And we also started showcasing the game at various events.

110
00:05:45,917 --> 00:05:49,318
And because we did that, we went at PAX East in Boston,

111
00:05:49,559 --> 00:05:51,879
and there we ran into Richard Hammer,

112
00:05:52,620 --> 00:05:53,940
who played the game on the show floor,

113
00:05:54,020 --> 00:05:56,201
and then later that night we ended up in his car.

114
00:05:56,778 --> 00:06:01,840
going to his Airbnb where we made a temporary live streaming setup where he played Move or Die live.

115
00:06:03,201 --> 00:06:08,903
NortonLine played the game on the show floor and then he followed up with several videos about

116
00:06:08,943 --> 00:06:14,585
Move or Die that kind of totaled in around 400,000 views. And Jesse Cox also played the

117
00:06:14,605 --> 00:06:18,666
game on the show floor and during the co-optional podcast he kind of nodded his head.

118
00:06:18,886 --> 00:06:23,728
Uh, Move or Die. Oh yeah! Move or Die is fun. One year anniversary update. Twitch integration.

119
00:06:24,848 --> 00:06:25,008
Yeah.

120
00:06:25,856 --> 00:06:29,199
Also the Giant Bomb guys played the game and then they mentioned us on their panel.

121
00:06:29,339 --> 00:06:33,924
One thing I really liked though is that I really liked at the AniMega booth was this thing called Move or Die.

122
00:06:34,404 --> 00:06:34,604
Woo!

123
00:06:35,345 --> 00:06:38,608
I think I got that on the subscreen.

124
00:06:38,628 --> 00:06:39,049
That was us.

125
00:06:39,089 --> 00:06:46,456
But yeah, and also during events we gave out promotional cards and some guys tried to sell those on eBay for $28.

126
00:06:47,036 --> 00:06:48,237
So it's kind of a compliment.

127
00:06:50,472 --> 00:06:52,473
But yeah, the release day came around,

128
00:06:52,733 --> 00:06:54,575
and we released the game in early 2016.

129
00:06:54,955 --> 00:06:57,397
So we spent one year in early access.

130
00:06:57,497 --> 00:07:00,119
And for those of you who haven't experienced this yet,

